#Control Variables:
#We add horsepower (hp), cylinder(cy) and price relative to per capita income(princ) in our regression which would impact the result. Since we want to figure out the omitted variables, we need to find out what is correlated to both price and quantity. Since the majority of people only need the horsepower and cylinder within a normal range when buying a car, as they get higher there will be fewer people buying the car. At the same time, larger horsepower and cylinder volume will result in a higher price since the costs are higher. Thus, omitting these two variables will lead the log price coefficient lower than it actually is. Similarly, as the price relative to per capita income gets higher, the price will be higher. When people cannot afford a car because the price relative to per capita income is large, the quantity will decrease. That is why missing the princ variable will make the coefficient lower than it actually is.

#Thus, we also plotted the correlation map showing as follows:
corrplot(cor(cardata_num),method='shade')

#The observed variables match what we have assumed.

#Fixed Effects:
#We add the interaction of year(ye) and model code(co), as well as the interaction of year(ye) and market(ma).
#Interaction of year(ye) and model code(co) is a concern because different years have different underlying demand for a specific car model and hence the firm has been offering different prices. 
#Interaction of year(ye) and market(ma) is another concern because there are cases when in specific years the market will be in a different economic environment, eg. Depression, and then the car will be priced lower and also the quantity will be lower.

#Potential Missing Values:
  #Short-term Competition: for example, if the competitors reduce the prices, we want to match their prices so it influences our pricing. Our demand decreases because they buy competitors products.

#According to the case, we assume from the iron_ore data that the amount of iron ore used to produce each car model is proportional to the weight. Thus, we try we as our instrumental variable since the price might be cost-driven instead of demand-driven. Cost changes does not relate to demand but price changes due to cost change can be used to establish causal relationship. We ran the regression as follows, keeping the controlled variables and fixed effects:

#My IV does not work.
#As we can see from the result, our regression results have low significance. Even though the correlation between price and weight is 0.67, the variance of price and weight is large and R-square is only 0.46, which means the regression in weight and prices only explains 46% of data. The IV does not work probably because the cost does not solely depend on iron but also other materials. What is more, style and other attributes contribute more to certain models and this would break the assumption that the weight is highly correlated to prices.

#Profit = (P - VC)*Q
#Profit = P^1+1*e^0*e^ - VC*e^0*e^*P^1
#We then can calculate the derivate of it from the price and then we could find the percentage relationship between VC and Price
#we could do it as the following process
#Profit' = (1+1) * P^1 * e^0 * e^ - 1 * P(1-1) * VC * e^0 * e^
#log(VC) = log(1+1) - log(1) + log(P)
#VC = P * (1 +1)/1

#7.
#To calculate cross elasticities, we have included the rival products price log(avgurprrival) into our regression. The coefficient of log(avgurprrival) is 1.98, which means a 1% increase in the price of the rival product will result in 1.98% of our sales. This gives us the cross-price elasticity of demand. From the earlier calculation, we have found the customers are very price sensitive. We expect that customers will quickly react and find cheaper alternatives when there is a price increase in our rival product. Thus, we expect the coefficient to be positive and bigger than one and our calculated coefficient satisfies these criteria. The large cross-elasticities means the market is very competitive because customers will easily switch to other substitutes when the price rises. 
reg7=felm(log(qu)~log(eurpr)+log(avgurprrival)+ma|factor(ye)+factor(co),data=cardata)
summary(reg7)
